t2709.text: Let’s hope this works because I don’t think we have a plan D. We are really hoping that Edge and YouTube are accessible for our students in other countries. We know it doesn’t work in some, but it appears the alternative solutions also don’t work reliably.

t2710.text: We redesign the course again around the original MOOC that it is based on, with additional resources, activities, and assessment tasks. Slack will be our fallback method of communication in addition to optional Zoom sessions for those who can make it.

t2711.text: Then many of our international students are instructed by their home governments to return home. Given the various time zones, a live Zoom meeting is even less viable.

t2712.text: @barbaramasser prepares a backup plan with self-paced activities for those who can’t reliably connect with Zoom.

t2713.text: Attending a few large Zoom meetings and seeing what goes on, we start to have doubts that our class of 120 will function on Zoom.

t2714.text: We redesign the course based around weekly structured Zoom workshops with shared online activities. We train the tutors in this new model.

t2715.text: As week 4 approaches, it becomes clear that face to face teaching in our workshop format is not viable.

t2716.text: Travel ban is announced so we delay the start of the course for four weeks to allow some of our students to join us. Course profile amended with new dates for course and assessment tasks. We prepare the tutors.

t2717.text: This will likely be a familiar story for many academics right now. Before semester @barbaramasser and I prepared the course website and organised the activity plans and printed all of the weekly workshop materials. #PSY2361
